[Event "Baker Bridge - 2-Over-1 Game Force"]
[Site ""]
[Date ""]
[Board "1"]
[Dealer "S"]
[Vulnerable "None"]
[Deal "S:KJ763.AQ7.J4.AQJ Q5.42.A9632.T963 A4.KJT8653.KQ.87 T982.9.T875.K542"]
[BoardVersionToken "ba9b2d969dcacca9f5aabb891a4e4c42a25b2fee1a4efc4484aa68cdfaf74d39"]
[Student "S"]
[Category "Bidding Conventions"]
[Difficulty "intermediate"]
[SkillPath "bidding_conventions/two_over_one"]
[Auction "S"]
1S Pass 2H Pass 3H Pass 3S =1= Pass 4C =2= Pass 4NT Pass 5S =3= Pass 6H Pass Pass Pass
[Note "1:control"]
[Note "2:control"]
[Note "3:2 keycards + trump Q"]
{How do you open the bidding?
With 18 HCP and a balanced hand, you open 1\S.  Partner responds  2\H. What do you rebid?
You know this is a 5-card suit, and bid 3\H, confirming the 8+card trump fit and sets the trump suit.
Partner rebids 3\S, a control bid, showing first or second round control.  (Some will play this as showing 3-card support for spades, but I recommend playing this as a control bid.).  
You bid 4C, also a control bid, showing first or second round control in clubs.  Partner bids 4NT, a keycard request using 1430.   

You bid 5\s, showing two keycards and the trump queen.  Partner bids the slam.
The slam is a good one. If either the \SQ or \CK is right there are 12 tricks by way of a finesse. But the best way to play the hand would be to try to establish a \S in the South hand, and if that fails try the \C finesse.}

[Event ""]
[Site ""]
[Date ""]
[Board "3"]
[Dealer "N"]
[Vulnerable "EW"]
[Deal "N:9754.T6.J72.8653 AJT.AK985.K96.Q7 KQ2.QJ42.T853.92 863.73.AQ4.AKJT4"]
[BoardVersionToken "a0a8edcc0e377065cd05649a78f2b1ee923048d6ede7fb100020c29192e4b25f"]
[Student "S"]
[Category "Bidding Conventions"]
[Difficulty "intermediate"]
[SkillPath "bidding_conventions/two_over_one"]
[Auction "N"]
Pass 1H Pass 2C Pass 2NT Pass 3NT Pass 4NT Pass 6NT Pass Pass Pass
{East opens 1\H - how should you respond?
East rebids 2NT.  How do you continue?
West shows her minimum by bidding 3NT.
East continues with 4NT - what does this mean?  How do you continue?

 East's 4NT was not Blackwood, but rather a quantitative raise in Notrump, and an invitation to slam.
You have 15 points, and they are good ones. So you accept the invitation and bid 6NT.
There are 11 top tricks. A 3-3 \H split would provide the 12th winner, but this is against the odds. Better to try two \S finesses, a 75% chance.}

[Event ""]
[Site ""]
[Date ""]
[Board "5"]
[Dealer "E"]
[Vulnerable "NS"]
[Deal "E:KT.98762.T72.AK2 AJ8752.AK.Q6.J87 94.JT54.853.QT53 Q63.Q3.AKJ94.964"]
[BoardVersionToken "343a95e8aef2726db19c9efbca9f4a1190d49f1e5af9f38c768afe611e822182"]
[Student "S"]
[Category "Bidding Conventions"]
[Difficulty "intermediate"]
[SkillPath "bidding_conventions/two_over_one"]
[Auction "E"]
Pass 1S Pass 2D Pass 2S Pass 4S Pass Pass Pass
{South opens 1\S -  
You responds 2\D, natural and game forcing.  South rebids 2\s.  In our style of 2/1, this promises 6+ cards in spades, and denies a side 4-card suit.  What should we bid now? 

You should jump to 4\S. This is Fast Arrival, indicating a minimum hand with no particular interest in slam.
South is happy to rest in the game contract.
Even with a combined 30 points, 10 tricks are certainly not a sure thing. South must hope that East holds the trump King.}

